<head>RECTITUDE</head>
    <list type="altnames">
<item>FAIRNESS</item>
<item>JUSTNESS</item>
<item>FAIR PLAY</item>
<item>FAIR-MINDEDNESS</item>
<item>EQUITY</item>
<item>EVENHANDEDNESS</item>
<item>IMPARTIALITY</item>
<item>OBJECTIVITY</item>
<item>NEUTRALITY</item>
<item>DISINTERESTEDNESS</item>
<item>HONESTY</item>
<item>RIGHTEOUSNESS</item>
<item>MORALS</item>
<item>MORALITY</item>
    </list>
    <list type="translations">
        <item xml:lang="zh">義務</item>
    </list>
<div type="definition">
<p>VIRTUE which consists in an ENDURING DESIRE to ACT CONFORMING to what is APPROPRIATE.</p>
    </div>
<div type="notes">
<div type="old-chinese-criteria">
<p>1. The most general word is yì 義 "rectitude" which is often used to refer to what is proper and what is one's proper duty in general and also duties in particular.</p>
<p>2. Rèn 任 refers to duties insofar as these impose burdens of responsibility.</p>
<p>3. Zé 責 refers to duties insofar as these represent demands that others do make or can make on one.</p>
<p>4. Zhí 職 refers specifically to official public duties that are part of one's public office.</p>
        </div>
<div type="modern-chinese-criteria">
<p>義務</p>
